# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: university-of-pittsburgh
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/2012-university-of-pittsburgh-bomb-threats] In 2012, a series of bomb threats was made towards the University of Pittsburgh.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/2012-university-of-pittsburgh-bomb-threats] The first threat was written on a bathroom stall in the Chevron Science Center and was observed on February 13, 2012.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/2012-university-of-pittsburgh-bomb-threats] It was not until approximately a month later, however, that threats occurred with increasing frequency.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/2012-university-of-pittsburgh-bomb-threats] The number of bomb threats totaled approximately 160 as of April 21, 2012, after which police reported no additional related threats.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/2012-university-of-pittsburgh-bomb-threats] Several threats were written on bathroom stalls in the Cathedral of Learning and Chevron Science Center.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/2012-university-of-pittsburgh-bomb-threats] Several more are known to have originated via email.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/2012-university-of-pittsburgh-bomb-threats] Some of the emails are believed to have been routed through intermediate servers using Mixmaster, a type of anonymous remailer that makes the origin of an email almost impossible to determine.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/2012-university-of-pittsburgh-bomb-threats] The FBI and Secret Service had identified at least one person of interest related to the case, and local police collaborated with the Department of Justice and the Joint Terrorism Task Force.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/2012-university-of-pittsburgh-bomb-threats] On April 11, police arrested Mark Lee Krangle, a Pitt alumnus and former teaching fellow who wrote a harassing email to Pitt professors that advised international terrorism was behind the bomb threats, as he disembarked at Pittsburgh International Airport.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/2012-university-of-pittsburgh-bomb-threats] On the same day, the Pittsburgh US Attorney's Office claimed that "significant progress" had been made in the investigation of the bomb threats.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/2012-university-of-pittsburgh-bomb-threats] The University of Pittsburgh offered a reward of up to $10,000 on March 30 "for information leading to an arrest and conviction" of those responsible for the threats, which was raised to up to $50,000 on April 2 before being withdrawn on April 21.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/2012-university-of-pittsburgh-bomb-threats] The University has also removed some bathroom stall doors in the Cathedral of Learning and ramped up security in the building.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/2012-university-of-pittsburgh-bomb-threats] This policy was soon changed to allow backpacks into buildings, and on April 9 the Cathedral of Learning had more than one open entrance (All guarded by security).
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/2012-university-of-pittsburgh-bomb-threats] On April 10, the Pittsburgh Post-Gazette received a note from "The Threateners" demanding that the University of Pittsburgh take down the $50,000 reward they offered for information leading to the culprit or culprits.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/2012-university-of-pittsburgh-bomb-threats] They offered a 24-hour window without bomb threats, which they upheld.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/2012-university-of-pittsburgh-bomb-threats] Pitt and the FBI decided to not negotiate with terrorists, ignoring the demand, and the Post-Gazette did not publish a story about the offer.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/2012-university-of-pittsburgh-bomb-threats] Then, on April 20, 2012, The Pitt News, the daily student newspaper, received a similar email from "The Threateners" offering a 24-hour window without threats, which they stuck to, and then demanded that Pitt takes down the $50,000 reward.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/2012-university-of-pittsburgh-bomb-threats] They also claimed to have no ties to any persons of interest Pitt has identified.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/2012-university-of-pittsburgh-bomb-threats] The Pitt News notified the university that it was writing a story about the offer, which led the University of Pittsburgh to withdraw the $50,000 reward by the morning of April 21, 2012.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/2012-university-of-pittsburgh-bomb-threats] Since the morning of April 21, there have been no more bomb threats at the University of Pittsburgh.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/2012-university-of-pittsburgh-bomb-threats] The university's final count of bomb threats was 160, targeting 52 buildings that lead to 136 evacuations.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/2012-university-of-pittsburgh-bomb-threats] On August 15, 2012, it was reported that Adam Busby of Dublin, Ireland was indicted in connection with the e-mailed threats.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/2012-university-of-pittsburgh-bomb-threats] As of November 6, 2013 no updates on Adam Busby's involvement have been published.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/2012-university-of-pittsburgh-bomb-threats] In addition, there have been no indictments whatsoever for the two months of bomb threats at the University of Pittsburgh that occurred before the concluding weeks of threats for which Busby has been indicted.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/acc-athlete-of-the-year] The **Atlantic Coast Conference Athlete of the Year** award is given to the male and female athlete who show extraordinary talent throughout the entire season.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/acc-athlete-of-the-year] The award is decided by members of the Atlantic Coast Sports Media Association.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/acc-athlete-of-the-year] McKevlin Award, which originally went to the league's athlete of the year regardless of gender until 1990, named in honor of a former sports editor of the *Raleigh News and Observer*, has been voted upon and handed out annually since the ACC was formed in 1953–1954.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/acc-athlete-of-the-year] In 1990, The Mary Garber Award, named in honor of Mary Garber, a former *Winston-Salem Journal* reporter and a pioneer for women in the field of sports journalism, was established to honor the league's top female athlete.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/acc-athlete-of-the-year] In 2005, the Associated Press Sports Editors (APSE) distinguished Garber by honoring her with its prestigious Red Smith Award, making her the first female recipient in the award's 25-year history.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/acc-championship-game] The **ACC Championship Game** is an annual American college football game held in early December by the Atlantic Coast Conference (ACC) each year to determine its football champion.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/acc-championship-game] From its inception in 2005 to 2019, and from 2021 to 2022, the game pit the champion of the Coastal Division against the champion of the Atlantic Division in a game that followed the conclusion of the regular season.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/acc-championship-game] Starting with the 2023 season, the ACC eliminated the divisions, and the top two teams with the best conference record meet in the championship game in Charlotte, North Carolina.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/acc-championship-game] Duke is the current conference champion after defeating Virginia in the 2025 championship game.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/acc-championship-game] The Atlantic Division was represented by either Clemson or Florida State in twelve of fifteen years through 2019, including eleven straight from 2009 to 2019, and five straight by Clemson from 2015 to 2019.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/acc-championship-game] The Coastal Division was represented by either Georgia Tech or Virginia Tech for the first eight games from 2005 to 2012, but from 2013 to 2019 all seven Coastal teams each represented the division after Virginia won in 2019.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/acc-championship-game] North Carolina State, Syracuse, California and Stanford have yet to make an appearance.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/acc-championship-game] Clemson in 2018 became the first team to win four consecutive ACC Championship Games, on the heels of FSU winning three straight.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/acc-championship-game] The Tigers then extended the record to five straight titles in 2019 and six straight in 2020.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/acc-championship-game] Their streak ended in 2021 when the Pittsburgh Panthers won the game, beating Wake Forest.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/acc-championship-game] When there were ACC football divisions, Atlantic Division winners went on to win the ACC Championship Game for nine consecutive years from 2011 to 2019, and were 11–5 in the game overall.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/acc-championship-game] The Coastal teams won four consecutive years from 2007 to 2010, but did not win again until 2021.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/acc-championship-game] There are no football divisions from the 2023 season onwards, the game instead pitting the two ACC teams with the highest conference winning percentage against each other.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/acc-championship-game] For the 2020 season, Notre Dame joined the ACC for conference play in football due to the COVID-19 pandemic and played in the first ever division-less format for the game.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/acc-championship-game] The ACC Championship Game is held at Bank of America Stadium in Charlotte, North Carolina each year, after being held in Florida (Jacksonville and Tampa) for its first five years.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/acc-championship-game] It is to remain a permanent fixture in Charlotte through at least 2030.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/acc-championship-game] The game's corporate sponsor was Dr Pepper from 2005 through the 2018 game.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/acc-championship-game] Before the 2004 college football season, the Atlantic Coast Conference determined its champion via round-robin play during the course of the regular season and there was no conference championship game.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/acc-championship-game] In 2004, the Atlantic Coast conference added two teams—Virginia Tech and Miami—expanding the league to 11 teams.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/acc-championship-game] At the time, college football teams were limited by the NCAA to 11 regular-season games, three or four of which typically featured teams outside the home team's conference.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/acc-championship-game] Following the 2004 season, the league added a 12th team—Boston College—and became eligible to hold a championship game at the conclusion of the 2005 season.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/acc-championship-game] The conference was divided into two divisions of six teams each.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/acc-championship-game] The team with the best conference record in each division is selected to participate in the championship game.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/acc-championship-game] In the inaugural championship game, which took place at the end of the 2005 college football season, the Florida State Seminoles defeated Virginia Tech 27–22 at Alltel Stadium in Jacksonville, Florida.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/acc-championship-game] In the 2006 game, two other teams faced off as Georgia Tech played Wake Forest.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/acc-championship-game] For the 2007 game, Jacksonville was awarded a one-year extension as host, and the game remained in Jacksonville.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/acc-championship-game] Virginia Tech returned to the ACC Football Championship game and faced off against Boston College.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/acc-championship-game] Tech won the game, 30–16, and returned to the championship in 2008 to defeat Boston College again 30–12.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/acc-championship-game] In 2009, Georgia Tech defeated Clemson, 39–34, but was forced to vacate the ACC championship by the NCAA.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/acc-championship-game] Following the 2007 game the Gator Bowl Committee—organizers of the ACC Football Championship game in Jacksonville—announced they would not seek another contract extension due to falling attendance.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/acc-championship-game] With Jacksonville's withdrawal from future site selection, the ACC selected Tampa, Florida and Charlotte, North Carolina as future sites of the game.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/acc-championship-game] The 2008 and 2009 games were held in Tampa and the 2010, 2011, 2012, and 2013 games were held in Charlotte before it was announced as the extended home of this game through at least 2019.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/acc-championship-game] After a political dispute led to a one-game 2016 foray to Orlando, the ACC Championship Game has been played in Charlotte ever since.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/acc-championship-game] This means that the ACC Championship will no longer be determined by the two division winners, but will instead have the two teams with the highest conference winning percentage face each other.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/acc-championship-game] In 1990, the eight-team Atlantic Coast Conference added Florida State to the league, creating a new nine-team ACC.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/acc-championship-game] Though Florida State was the only school added to the conference, some league officials discussed offering one or more other schools—Navy, Pittsburgh, Syracuse, South Carolina, Miami, West Virginia, Boston College, Rutgers, or Virginia Tech—an offer to join the league.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/acc-championship-game] For various reasons, however, no other team was extended an offer.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/acc-championship-game] Throughout the 1990s, the Atlantic Coast Conference remained at nine members.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/acc-championship-game] Ironically, South Carolina was a charter member of the ACC that left in 1971.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/acc-championship-game] The nearby Southeastern Conference (SEC), which also encompasses college football teams in the American South, also expanded in 1990.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/acc-championship-game] Instead of adding one team, as did the ACC, the then 10-team SEC added two—the University of Arkansas and the University of South Carolina.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/acc-championship-game] The expansion made the SEC the first 12-school football conference and thus the first eligible to hold a conference championship game under NCAA rules (the first game was held in 1992).
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/acc-championship-game] The SEC enjoyed increased television ratings and revenue through the 1990s and by 2003 was earning over $100 million annually, with revenues shared out among member schools.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/acc-championship-game] Officials of other leagues took note of the financial boon that followed SEC expansion to twelve teams.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/acc-championship-game] Atlantic Coast Conference representatives began discussing expansion to twelve schools in the first years of the new century, who began publicly pursuing the possibility of expansion anew in 2003.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/acc-championship-game] On May 13, 2003, representatives voted in favor of extending invitations to three schools.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/acc-championship-game] The only certain school was the University of Miami, while the other two spots were still being debated.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/acc-championship-game] Initially, the league favored admitting Miami, Syracuse University, and Boston College.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/acc-championship-game] After a month of debate, however, the ACC elected to extend formal invitations to Miami, Boston College, and Virginia Tech, which joined after initially being overlooked.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/acc-championship-game] This came years after these schools were considered for ACC membership in the early 1990s but nothing had ever came to fruition.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/acc-championship-game] Pittsburgh and Syracuse would also eventually join the ACC after rejections in 1990 and 2003, becoming members in 2013.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/acc-championship-game] Miami and Virginia Tech began official ACC play with the 2004 college football season.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/acc-championship-game] After the league settled a lawsuit resulting from the departure of the three former Big East Conference teams, Boston College began ACC play in the 2005 season.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/acc-championship-game] With the league officially at 12 teams, it became eligible to hold a conference championship football game.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/acc-championship-game] Even before the announcement proclaiming the ACC's expansion to 12 teams, several cities and sports organizations were preparing bids to host the ACC Football Championship Game.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/acc-championship-game] The prospect of tens of thousands of visitors could provide a multimillion-dollar economic boost for a host city and region while requiring few, if any, additional facilities.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/acc-championship-game] One early contender was the city of Charlotte, North Carolina.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/acc-championship-game] Even before Virginia Tech, Miami, and Boston College were chosen as the ACC's picks to expand, Carolinas Stadium Corporation, the owner and operator of Charlotte's Ericsson Stadium (as it was called then) lobbied heavily for Charlotte's selection.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/acc-championship-game] Other early options included Orlando, Tampa, Atlanta, and Jacksonville.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/acc-championship-game] Shortly after negotiations for the location of the game began during the spring of 2004, the ACC announced that it had signed a new, seven-year television contract with ABC and ESPN.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/acc-championship-game] As part of the deal, the ACC would earn over $40 million in revenue a year in exchange for the networks' exclusive right to televise the ACC Football Championship Game along with several high-profile regular season games.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/acc-championship-game] Revenues would be divided among the 12 ACC member schools.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/acc-championship-game] In July 2004 the ACC began deliberations about which bid to accept.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/acc-championship-game] On August 19, 2004, league officials announced that Jacksonville would host the game in 2005 and 2006.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/acc-championship-game] The league would then have the option to re-select Jacksonville for an additional one or two-year contract.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/acc-championship-game] Charlotte was the first runner-up in the competition.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/acc-championship-game] For its first three years, the championship game was held at EverBank Field (known as *Alltel Stadium* in 2005 and 2006 and *Jacksonville Municipal Stadium* in 2007).
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/acc-championship-game] That contract expired after the 2007 season.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/acc-championship-game] In December 2007, the ACC awarded the next four games to Tampa (first two) and Charlotte (next two).
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/acc-championship-game] Raymond James Stadium was the venue for the Tampa games in 2008 and 2009, while the Bank of America Stadium provided the venue for the Charlotte games in 2010 and 2011.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/acc-championship-game] Charlotte hosted the game again in 2012 and 2013.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/acc-championship-game] In February 2014 it was announced that Charlotte would continue to host the game through at least 2019.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/acc-championship-game] However, in response to North Carolina's Public Facilities Privacy & Security Act (HB2), the ACC voted in September 2016 to move the 2016 championship out of North Carolina.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/acc-championship-game] Following the absorption of Virginia Tech and Miami into the ACC, questions arose about how an 11-team league could fairly select participants in the conference championship game.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/acc-championship-game] A divisional structure involving two six-team divisions competing for two championship-game slots would not be possible.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/acc-championship-game] In addition, the ACC could not continue to select its champion via round-robin play since there were now 11 teams and only seven or eight conference games available per team.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/acc-championship-game] Even the NCAA's addition of a 12th game to the regular season did little to relieve the conference's problem.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/acc-championship-game] Prior to the 2004 college football season, the ACC requested a waiver to the NCAA's rule requiring conferences to have 12-plus teams before having a conference championship game.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/acc-championship-game] Before the season began, however, the NCAA rejected the ACC's application, and the league had to use a semi-round-robin format to select a champion during the 2004 football season.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/acc-championship-game] After that season, the inclusion of Boston College as the ACC's 12th team solved the problem of enabling the ACC to have a championship football game.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/acc-championship-game] On October 18, 2004, the ACC announced its new football structure with two divisions.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/acc-championship-game] Each six-team division plays a round-robin schedule within the division and a rotation of three conference games against teams from the opposing division.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/acc-championship-game] The two teams with the best conference records in each division earn places to the championship game.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/acc-championship-game] In the event of a tie in records within one division, divisional records and the results of head-to-head games are considered.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/acc-championship-game] Also, in the games between the two divisions, each team has a permanent rival team that is played every year.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/acc-championship-game] Hence, every year, there are these football games: Georgia Tech vs.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/acc-championship-game] On July 28, 2022, the ACC announced a revised football structure, eliminating divisions entirely, coming off the heels of the NCAA Division I Council's announcement that conferences no longer need to maintain divisions to hold a championship.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/acc-championship-game] Instead of a divisional structure where teams play a round-robin schedule within their division, it will instead move to a 3-5-5 format.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/acc-championship-game] Each team will have three designated permanent matchups, who they will face every year (mostly reserved for rivalry games such as North Carolina vs.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/acc-championship-game] Miami), along with two different 5-team rotations that swap every year, such that every team will have at least one home game and one away game against every other team in a four-year cycle.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/acc-championship-game] Under this format, the two ACC teams with the highest conference winning percentage will be eligible to play in the championship.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/acc-championship-game] Notre Dame joined the conference as a non-football member in 2014 and, while playing five ACC teams each season, is not eligible for the championship game.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/acc-championship-game] However, for the 2020 season, Notre Dame joined the ACC for conference play and the ACC used a division-less format for the game, with the game contested by the two teams with the best conference records.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/acc-championship-game] Below are the results from all ACC Championship Games played.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/acc-championship-game] The winning team appears in bold font, on a background of their primary team color.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/acc-championship-game] Rankings are from the AP Poll released prior to the game.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/acc-championship-game] † Georgia Tech was forced to vacate their 2009 win due to NCAA violations. ‡ 2020 game attendance capped due to the COVID-19 pandemic in North Carolina.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/acc-championship-game] The ACC Championship game has featured a rematch of a regular-season game a total of six times (2007, 2008, 2009, 2011, 2020, 2025).
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/acc-championship-game] The team which won the regular-season game is 2–4 in the rematches, winning in 2009 and 2011 but losing in 2007, 2008, 2020, and 2025.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/acc-men-s-basketball-tournament] The **ACC men's basketball tournament** (popularly known as the **ACC tournament**) is the conference championship tournament in men's basketball for the Atlantic Coast Conference (ACC).
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/acc-men-s-basketball-tournament] It has been held every year since the ACC's first basketball season concluded in 1954 (with the 2020 tournament only being partially completed due to the COVID-19 pandemic).
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/acc-men-s-basketball-tournament] The ACC tournament is a single-elimination tournament and seeding is based on regular season records.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/acc-men-s-basketball-tournament] The winner, declared conference champion, receives the conference's automatic bid to the NCAA men's tournament.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/acc-men-s-basketball-tournament] Since July 1, 1961, the ACC's bylaws have included the phrase "and the winner shall be the conference champion" in referring to the tournament, meaning that the conference tournament winner is the only champion of the ACC.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/acc-men-s-basketball-tournament] The second Charlotte Coliseum on Tyvola Road opened in 1988 and closed in 2005 after the construction of a new arena in Uptown Charlotte.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/acc-men-s-soccer-tournament] The **ACC men's soccer tournament** is the conference championship tournament in soccer for the Atlantic Coast Conference (ACC).
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/acc-men-s-soccer-tournament] The tournament has been held every year since 1987.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/acc-men-s-soccer-tournament] It is a single-elimination tournament and seeding is based on regular season records.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/acc-men-s-soccer-tournament] The winner, declared conference champion, receives the conference's automatic bid to the NCAA Division I men's soccer championship.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/acc-men-s-soccer-tournament] Beginning in 2024, the tournament expanded from 12 teams to 15, with the No.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/acc-men-s-soccer-tournament] 1 seed receiving a first-round bye; seeds 2-8 hosting first-round games; No.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/acc-men-s-soccer-tournament] 1 seed and top remaining seeds in each bracket hosting quarterfinal games.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/acc-men-s-soccer-tournament] The semifinals and championship game are all played at the same location.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/acc-men-s-soccer-tournament] Virginia is the most winning team of the ACC tournament with 11 conference titles.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/acc-men-s-soccer-tournament] Florida State, Georgia Tech, and Miami do not sponsor men's soccer.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/acc-men-s-soccer-tournament] Teams in *italics* no longer sponsor soccer in the ACC.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/acc-men-s-soccer-tournament] Prior to 1987, the champion was determined based on regular season play.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/acc-network] The network's digital platform, **ACC Network Extra** (**ACCNX**), carries ACC events not broadcast on television.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/acc-network] It streams on ESPN+, as well as ESPN.com and the ESPN app for ACC Network subscribers.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/acc-network] There had been repeated calls for the ACC to establish its own cable channel, similar to those that had or were being established by other Power Five conferences.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/acc-network] The Big Ten and Pac-12 had already launched their own channels, while ESPN and the SEC had announced the SEC Network would launch in 2014.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/acc-network] SEC Network's first year of operation increased the conference's television revenue by around $100 million.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/acc-network] In discussions with ESPN management, there were uncertainties over whether an ACC channel would be economically viable, due to cord cutting and changing television viewing habits.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/acc-network] The stability of the ACC itself was also questioned, but was addressed in 2013 by requiring the conference's current teams to grant the ACC control of media rights to all home games through the 2026–2027 season, even if they leave the conference.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/acc-network] This policy effectively discourages schools from leaving the ACC, and left the SEC as the only Power Five conference to not have a similar grant requirement.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/acc-network] On July 21, 2016, at a media event in Charlotte, North Carolina, ESPN announced a 20-year extension of its contract with the ACC, and that it would launch a cable channel dedicated to the ACC in 2019 known as the ACC Network.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/acc-network] The announcement was attended by then-ESPN president John Skipper and ACC commissioner John Swofford.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/acc-network] Ahead of the television network's launch, ESPN announced that it would begin to stream ACC events beginning in the upcoming 2016 season.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/acc-network] Following the announcement, Skipper defended the decision to go on with launching a linear television network, arguing that sports were the most valuable property on television because they are "the only thing you have to watch live".
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/acc-network] Each ACC school constructed production facilities so they can contribute programming to the channel.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/acc-network] Its operations are based out of ESPN's main studios in Bristol, but some programming originates from Charlotte, North Carolina (where SEC Network, and formerly ESPNU, also operate).
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/acc-network] In November 2018, it was officially announced that ACCN would launch on August 22, 2019.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/acc-network] Opening night programming included the ESPN Films documentary *The Class That Saved Coach K*, which chronicled Mike Krzyzewski's turnaround of the Duke Blue Devils basketball team in the 1980s.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/acc-network] It aired its first football game on August 29, with the defending national champion Clemson Tigers hosting the Georgia Tech Yellow Jackets.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/acc-network] In 2022, the ACC brought back old rivalries like the Backyard Brawl between the University of Pittsburgh Panthers and the West Virginia University Mountaineers.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/acc-network] A friendly rivalry between University of Pittsburgh Panthers and Georgia Tech Yellow Jackets in memory of the 1956 Sugar Bowl and Bobby Grier, during the last game, actor Anthony Mackie appeared on field to honor Grier and the game.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/acc-network] ACC Network is expected to carry 1,300 events per year.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/acc-network] To provide more content for the channel, the ACC agreed to expand its conference schedule in college basketball to 20 games by the 2019–20 season.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/acc-network] ESPN also acquired the secondary ACC rights previously sub-licensed to Raycom Sports for its syndicated *ACC Network* (the company will continue to be involved as a sub-contractee for events that can be carried by the new channel).
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/acc-network] Mark Packer and Wes Durham host the morning show *Packer and Durham*, simulcast on ACCN and SiriusXM.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/acc-network] *All ACC* will serve as the network's general news program, while *The Huddle* airs on Friday nights and Saturday mornings during football season.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/acc-network] As a prelude to the linear channel, and as part of ESPN's new rights package, ESPN's digital platform WatchESPN began to carry broadcasts of ACC sporting events not on television under the branding **ACC Network Extra**.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/acc-network] ESPN promoted that it would carry over 600 live telecasts per season.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/acc-network] ACCNX has continued its operations following the launch of the channel, becoming available exclusively to ACC Network subscribers.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/acc-network] ESPN stated in June 2017 that it had reached carriage deals for the ACC Network with unknown providers.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/acc-network] In October 2017, Altice USA committed to offering the channel as part of in its latest round of carriage negotiations with Disney.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/acc-network] On December 30, 2018, Disney reached a new carriage agreement with Verizon Fios, which included carriage of the ACC Network.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/acc-network] On March 12, 2019, agreement was reached with AT&T to carry the ACC Network on DirecTV at launch.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/acc-network] Live television streaming services Hulu, PlayStation Vue, YouTube TV and TVision Home also signed agreements to carry the channel at launch.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/acc-network] On August 14, Charter Spectrum, the largest cable provider in the ACC's heartland of North Carolina, agreed to carry ACCN as part of a new carriage agreement covering all Disney networks (including those acquired from 21st Century Fox).
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/acc-network] On August 29, Dish Network agreed to carry the network on both Dish satellite TV service and Sling TV streaming service just in time to broadcast the Clemson/Georgia Tech football game.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/acc-network] On September 4, Cox Communications agreed to carry the network.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/acc-network] On September 25, AT&T agreed to carry the network on both AT&T U-Verse and AT&T TV Now.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/acc-network] Deals were also made with the National Rural Telecommunications Cooperative (NRTC), National Cable Television Cooperative (NCTC) and Vivicast to carry the channel at launch on various smaller cable TV systems across the country.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/acc-network] In the ACC Network's first athletic year, ESPN successfully negotiated the network's carriage to 70 million households on all major cable and satellite TV providers, with the sole exception of Comcast.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/acc-network] The holdout, Comcast, which provides cable television to 19 million households as of Q3 2020, claimed in September 2019 that ESPN was not allowing them to carry the network at a "fair and reasonable cost" to their customers.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/acc-network] Following a two-year holdout, ESPN and Comcast eventually came to a deal to carry ACC Network on Xfinity in November 2021.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/acc-women-s-basketball-tournament] The **ACC women's basketball tournament** is the conference championship tournament in basketball for the Atlantic Coast Conference (ACC).
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/acc-women-s-basketball-tournament] The tournament has been held every year since 1978, several years before the first NCAA championships for women.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/acc-women-s-basketball-tournament] The winner, declared conference champion, receives the conference's automatic bid to the NCAA Women's Division I Basketball Championship.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p01] The **University of Pittsburgh** (**Pitt**) is a state-related research university in Pittsburgh, Pennsylvania, U.S.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p01] The university is composed of seventeen undergraduate and graduate schools and colleges at its urban Pittsburgh campus, home to the university's central administration and over 31,000 undergraduate and graduate students.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p01] The 132-acre Pittsburgh campus includes various historic buildings that are part of the Schenley Farms Historic District, most notably its 42-story Gothic revival centerpiece, the Cathedral of Learning.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p01] Pitt is a member of the Association of American Universities and is classified among "R1: Doctoral Universities – Very high research activity".
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p01] Pitt traces its roots to the **Pittsburgh Academy** founded by Hugh Henry Brackenridge in 1787.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p01] While the city was still on the edge of the American frontier at the time, Pittsburgh's rapid growth meant that a proper university was soon needed, and Pitt's charter was altered in 1819 to confer university status on it as the **Western University of Pennsylvania**.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p01] After surviving two fires and several relocations, the university moved to its current location in Pittsburgh's Oakland neighborhood, and by act of the state legislature was renamed the University of Pittsburgh in 1908.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p01] Pitt was a private institution until 1966, when it became part of the Commonwealth System of Higher Education.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p01] The campus is situated adjacent to the flagship medical facilities of its closely affiliated University of Pittsburgh Medical Center (UPMC) and its flagship hospital, UPMC Presbyterian, as well as the Carnegie Museums of Pittsburgh, Schenley Park, and Carnegie Mellon University.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p01] The university also operates four undergraduate branch campuses in Western Pennsylvania, located in Bradford, Greensburg, Johnstown, and Titusville.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p01] In athletics, Pitt competes in Division I of the NCAA as the Pittsburgh Panthers, primarily as members of the Atlantic Coast Conference.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p01] Founded by Hugh Henry Brackenridge as **Pittsburgh Academy** in 1787, the University of Pittsburgh is one of the few universities and colleges established in the 18th century in the United States.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p01] It is the oldest continuously chartered institution of learning in the U.S. west of the Allegheny Mountains.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p01] The school began as a preparatory school, presumably in a log cabin, possibly as early as 1770 in Western Pennsylvania, then a frontier.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p01] Brackenridge obtained a charter for the school from the state legislature of the Commonwealth of Pennsylvania on February 28, 1787, just ten weeks before the opening of the Constitutional Convention in Philadelphia.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p01] A brick building was erected in 1790 on the south side of Third Street and Cherry Alley for the Pittsburgh Academy.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p01] The small two-story brick building, with a gable facing the alley, contained three rooms: one below and two above.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p01] Within a short period, more advanced education in the area was needed, so in 1819 the Commonwealth of Pennsylvania amended the school's 1787 charter to confer university status.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p01] The school was named the **Western University of Pennsylvania**, or WUP, and was intended to be the western sister institution to the University of Pennsylvania in Philadelphia.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p01] By 1830, WUP had moved into a new three-story, freestone-fronted building, with Ionic columns and a cupola, near its original buildings fronting the south side of Third Street, between Smithfield Street and Cherry Alley in downtown Pittsburgh.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p01] By the 1830s, the university faced severe financial pressure to abandon its traditional liberal education in favor of the state legislature's desire for it to provide more vocational training.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p01] The decision to remain committed to liberal education nearly killed the university, but it persevered despite its abandonment by the city and state.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p01] The university's buildings, along with most of its records and files, were destroyed in the Great Fire of 1845 that wiped out 20 square blocks of Pittsburgh.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p01] Classes were temporarily held in Trinity Church until a new building was constructed on Duquesne Way (on what was the site of the former Horne's department store).
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p01] Four years later, in 1849, this building also was destroyed by fire.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p01] Due to the catastrophic nature of these fires, operations were suspended for a few years to allow the university time to regroup and rebuild.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p01] By 1854, WUP had erected a new building on the corner of Ross and Diamond (now Forbes Avenue) streets (site of the present day City-County building) and classes resumed in 1855.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p01] It is during this era, in 1867, that Samuel Pierpont Langley, astronomer, inventor, aviation pioneer and future Secretary of the Smithsonian Institution, was chosen as director of the Allegheny Observatory that was donated to WUP in 1865.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p01] Langley was professor of astronomy and physics and remained at WUP until 1891, when he was succeeded by another prominent astronomer, James Keeler.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p01] Growing quickly during this period, WUP outgrew its downtown facilities and the university moved its campus to Allegheny City (present-day North Side).
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p01] The university eventually found itself on a 10-acre (4.0 ha) site on the North Side's Observatory Hill at the location of its Allegheny Observatory.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p01] There, it constructed two new buildings, Science Hall and Main Hall, that were occupied by 1889 and 1890 respectively.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p01] During this era, the first collegiate football team was formed at Pitt in 1889.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p01] In 1892, the Western Pennsylvania Medical College was amalgamated into the university (now the University of Pittsburgh School of Medicine).
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p01] By 1893, the university had graduated its first African-American, William Hunter Dammond.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p01] In 1895 WUP established its School of Law, and Andrew Carnegie and George Westinghouse were elected to the board of trustees, where they joined Andrew Mellon, who had been elected in 1894.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p01] The Pittsburgh College of Pharmacy and Pittsburgh Dental School also joined the university in 1896.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p01] In 1898, the first women, sisters Margaret and Stella Stein, graduated from the university.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p01] During this period, university engineering professor Reginald Fessenden was conducting pioneering work in radio broadcasting.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p01] By 1904, playing at Exposition Park, the university had its first undefeated football team.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p01] Citing a need to avoid confusion, distinguish itself from the University of Pennsylvania, and return to its roots by identifying itself with the city, the Western University of Pennsylvania, by act of the state legislature, was renamed the **University of Pittsburgh** in the summer of 1908.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p01] During this time, the university had also outgrown its accommodations on what is now the North Side and its departments had been scattered throughout the city for years.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p01] To consolidate all of its components on one campus, WUP bought 43 acres (17 ha) of land in December 1907 in what is now the Oakland neighborhood of Pittsburgh and began relocating departments there by 1909.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p01] The initial campus plan for the new location centered on the winning submission from a national architectural contest that incorporated a Greek Acropolis design by Henry Hornbostel for 30 buildings.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p01] However, due to financial and other constraints, only four of the buildings were constructed in this style, of which only Thaw Hall remains today.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p01] In the fall of 1909, the university became the first college to adopt the panther as its mascot.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p01] It was also during this period that the university, led by Chancellor Samuel McCormick, again held off pressures to abandon the school's commitment to liberal education in favor of more technical-based training.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p01] During his administration, McCormick also led the university into a new level of national recognition, expansion, and growth, as well as beginning institutional support of athletics.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p01] In the 1920s, new university chancellor John Gabbert Bowman declared that he had a vision for a centerpiece "tall building" for the university.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p01] The 14-acre (5.7 ha) Frick Acres property in Oakland was soon purchased and plans for the campus shifted focus from the hillside to a neo-Gothic Revival plan that today comprises the Cathedral of Learning, Heinz Memorial Chapel, Stephen Foster Memorial, and Clapp Hall buildings.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p01] The building was financed by donors and by a campaign to collect dimes from local school children.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p01] Bowman was a persuasive leader and although the Great Depression intervened, the Cathedral of Learning, on which construction was begun in 1926, began hosting classes in 1931 and was formally dedicated in 1937.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p01] Today, it remains the second tallest university building in the world and contains an equally impressive interior highlighted by a 22,000-square-foot (2,000 m2) Gothic hall Commons Room with 52-foot-tall (16 m) arches currently surrounded by 31 Nationality Rooms.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p01] In the early 20th century, epidemics of polio began to hit the United States and other industrialized countries.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p01] As hospitals filled with patients in iron lungs, and tens of thousands were left disabled, the fear of polio grew, leading to the closing of many public facilities.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p01] Meanwhile, Jonas Salk had set up the University of Pittsburgh's Virus Research Lab in the basement of what is now Salk Hall.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p01] By 1951, Salk and his team had begun immunization experiments in monkeys using dead polio virus.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p01] Soon, however, Salk began to test inoculations in paralyzed polio patients and by 1953 human trials among the general population were initiated.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p01] By the spring of the following year, the largest controlled field trials in medical history were underway, and by 1955 the vaccine developed by Salk and his researchers was declared effective.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p01] By 1962, Salk's vaccine had reduced the incidence of polio in the United States by 95 percent.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p01] The breakthroughs in immunology and vaccine development at Pitt by Salk and his team are considered one of the most significant scientific and medical achievements in history.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p01] In 1966, Pitt was designated by Pennsylvania as a state-related university.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p01] As such, Pitt receives public funds ($154.3 million in fiscal year 2016) covering about 7% of its operating budget, and offers reduced tuition to Pennsylvania residents.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p01] Upon affiliation with the state, subsidized tuition led to a massive influx of new students and rapid expansion of Pitt's size and scope.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p01] In the 1970s, Pitt's football team returned to greatness with a national championship season in 1976 led by Hall of Fame running back Tony Dorsett and continued success in the 1980s with players such as Hall of Fame quarterback Dan Marino.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p01] In the 1980s, significant medical research in the field of organ transplantation was conducted by Thomas Starzl, establishing Pitt as the world leader in the field of organ transplantation.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p01] In 1991, chancellor Wesley Posvar retired after 24 years in office.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p01] His administration is best known for elimination of the university's debt from its 1960s financial crisis and for increasing the school's prestige and endowment.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p01] Under Posvar, Pitt's operating budget grew sevenfold to $630 million and its endowment tripled to $257 million.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p01] Mark Nordenberg was chancellor of the university from 1995 to 2014 and led Pitt through a period of substantial progress, including a $2-billion capital-raising campaign that is over three quarters of the way toward achieving its goal and a $1-billion 12-year facilities plan.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p01] Gallagher was named the 18th chancellor of the university and assumed the office on August 1, 2014.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p01] The University of Pittsburgh's main campus comprises approximately 132 urban acres (0.53 km2) located in Pittsburgh's historic Oakland neighborhood.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p01] Much of the campus, including its centerpiece 42-story Cathedral of Learning, falls within the Oakland Civic Center/Schenley Farms National Historic District. contains an eclectic mix of architecture that includes Greek revival, Neogothic, Italian Renaissance, and modern.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p01] The University of Pittsburgh's main campus contains four contiguous sections: upper (sports complexes, residence halls); mid (Benedum, Chevron, Allen and Thaw Halls); lower (Cathedral of Learning, Union, Posvar Hall); and on the west end of campus, the medical center complex.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p01] The campus is bordered by Darragh Street/McKee Place to the west and Bellefield Avenue/Dithridge Street to the east; Forbes and Fifth avenues traverse the campus from west to east.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p01] Although generally within walking distance, the university also runs a bus and shuttle service between various campus locations and bordering neighborhoods.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p01] The main campus is within walking distance of many recreational, cultural, and educational institutions in the Oakland neighborhood.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p01] The campus is adjacent to Schenley Plaza, the main branch of the Carnegie Public Library, the Carnegie Museums of Natural History and Art and the Carnegie Music Hall, as well as portions of Carnegie Mellon University.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p01] Carlow University is just west of campus, adjacent to the university's medical center complexes.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p01] The main quad of Carnegie Mellon University, Central Catholic High School, and historic Schenley Park, site of the Phipps Conservatory & Botanical Gardens, lie across Junction Hollow on the east end.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p01] Four Pitt buildings are individually listed on the National Register of Historic Places: Allegheny Observatory (in Pittsburgh's Riverview Park on the Northside), the Cathedral of Learning, the Pittsburgh Athletic Association building, and the Ford Motor building.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p01] Twenty-one of Pitt's buildings (including the 5 residence halls that make up Schenley Quadrangle, see below) are contributing properties to the Schenley Farms-Oakland Civic Center Historic District that has been listed on the National Register of Historic Places as a historic district.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p01] Due to the historical nature of various sites around Pitt's buildings, the Commonwealth of Pennsylvania has placed historical markers outside the Allegheny Observatory, Posvar Hall, Salk Hall, Stephen Foster Memorial, and the William Pitt Union.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p01] In addition, a Pennsylvania Historical Marker has been placed on campus near the Cathedral of Learning to mark the significance of the University of Pittsburgh itself.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p01] Nicholas Greek Orthodox Church, Schenley High School, Soldiers and Sailors Memorial Hall – where scenes of The Silence of the Lambs were filmed in 1990, and the Stephen Foster sculpture.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p01] Many of these buildings and their facilities are integrated into the events and activities of the university.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p01] The majority of Pitt-owned facilities are clustered in the Oakland neighborhood of Pittsburgh which includes the Schenley Farms Historic District, however a few prominent facilities are scattered elsewhere throughout the city, including the adjacent Shadyside neighborhood.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p01] The university also has a major archeological research site, the Allen L.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p01] Cook Spring Creek Preserve, near Rock River, Wyoming.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p01] Athletic facilities of the University of Pittsburgh Panthers that are located in Oakland in the upper campus and include the Charles L Cost Sports Center, Fitzgerald Field House, the Petersen Events Center, Trees Hall and Trees Field.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p01] An approximately $30 million upgrade of on-campus sports facilities, starting with the Petersen Sports Complex, includes new soccer, baseball, softball facilities, and helps clear a space for the future construction of a new track and field and band complex.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p01] Athletic facilities in Pittsburgh that are located outside of the Oakland neighborhood include Acrisure Stadium and the UPMC Sports Performance Complex.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p01] Major on-campus residence halls include the Litchfield Towers, Schenley Quadrangle, Forbes Hall, Bouquet Gardens and Ruskin Hall located on the lower campus, Lothrop Hall on the medical campus, and Panther, Nordenberg Hall, and Sutherland halls located on the upper campus.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p01] The University of Pittsburgh Medical Center (UPMC) is consistently ranked in U.S.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p01] Regional campuses allow students to complete entire degree programs (typically at lower tuition rates) or take preliminary courses and relocate to other regional campuses or the Oakland campus to finish their studies.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p01] The Pitt Regional Campus Tuition Pledge, announced in 2026, is offered at all four regional campuses, providing a tuition-free education to eligible Pennsylvania residents with an annual household income at or below $75,000.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p01] The University of Pittsburgh has been noted for both its role in community outreach and its impact on the economy of the city and the Western Pennsylvania region.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p01] Pitt was also listed as a "best neighbor" in the previous ranking released in 2006.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p01] These rankings reflect the statistics that each year Pitt spends more than $1.7 billion in the community and supports nearly 33,800 jobs in Allegheny County.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p01] The university is the Pittsburgh region's second largest non-government employer behind its affiliated University of Pittsburgh Medical Center (UPMC).
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p01] Pitt's research program alone imports more than $822 million into the region each year (more than $3.60 for each $1 of state appropriations), and supports some 23,100 local jobs.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p01] Pitt students also spend more than $213 million on goods, services, and rental payments within the local economy.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p01] Pitt ranked sixth in the number of startups spawned by technologies developed by its researchers according to Association of University Technology Managers.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p01] Pitt and its medical school are the academic partners of the closely affiliated the University of Pittsburgh Medical Center.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p01] With over 1450 employees and $1 billion annual revenue, UPMC is the largest non-government employer in Pennsylvania.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p01] Through the Pitt Volunteer Pool, faculty and staff members donate more than 10,000 hours annually to community service projects for agencies such as the Salvation Army, Pittsburgh AIDS Task Force, and Greater Pittsburgh Community Food Bank.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p01] Pitt is a leading producer of Peace Corps volunteers.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p01] According to the Peace Corps' 2008 ranking of colleges and universities, only 14 schools in the nation produced more Peace Corps volunteers.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p01] Pitt's graduate school also ranked tenth for most alumni Peace Corps volunteers.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p01] The University of Pittsburgh has undertaken programs to improve sustainability initiatives and practices.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p01] Pitt started programs in ecology and established biological field stations in 1926.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p01] In 1990, Pitt was one of the first 22 signatories of the Talloires Declaration.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p01] In 2003, Pitt founded its Mascaro Center for Sustainable Innovation.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p01] In 2013, Pitt released its first sustainability report and in 2014 celebrated a "Year of Sustainability" by launching a Student Office of Sustainability that now has over 25 affiliated student organizations.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p01] In 2018, Pitt published its first comprehensive "Pitt Sustainability Plan", established the Office of Sustainability, and hired its first director of sustainability.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p01] In 2020, Pitt committed to achieving carbon neutrality by 2037 (its 250th anniversary) and its first climate action plan came out in 2022.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p01] In 2018, the university announced its intention to buy all of the electricity from a run-of-the-river hydro power facility to be built by Rye Development at Allegheny Lock and Dam No.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p01] In 2020, the university announced a second local renewable power purchasing agreement, for solar power to be built on the border of Beaver and Allegheny counties near Pittsburgh International Airport.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p01] The university has been criticized for some of its financial investments, namely those in the fossil fuel industry.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p01] In 2020, a Board report disclosed that endowment exposure to fossil fuels had decreased 42% between 2015 and 2020, with zero private investments in fossil fuels by the end of 2035.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p01] The university was chartered by the Commonwealth of Pennsylvania in 1787 and it operated as a fully private institution until an alteration to its charter in 1966 at which point it became part of the Commonwealth System of Higher Education.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p01] Legally, however, the university remains a private entity, operating under its nonprofit corporate charter, governed by its independent Board of Trustees, and with its assets under its own ownership and control.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p01] Therefore, it retains the freedom and individuality of a private institution, both administratively and academically, setting its own standards for admissions, awarding of degrees, faculty qualifications, teaching, and staff hiring.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p01] It is made up of 36 voting members: chancellor, 17 term trustees elected by the board, 6 alumni trustees elected by the board on nomination from the Alumni Association Board of directors, and 12 Commonwealth trustees.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p01] The governor of Pennsylvania, the president pro tempore of the Pennsylvania Senate, and the speaker of the Pennsylvania House of Representatives each appoints four of the 12 Commonwealth trustees.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p01] Additional non-voting trustees include 14 special trustees and additional emeritus trustees selected by the board.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p01] Non-voting ex-officio members include the governor of Pennsylvania, the secretary of the Commonwealth of Pennsylvania, the chief executive of Allegheny County, and the mayor of Pittsburgh.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p01] There are three or more regular meetings of the Board of Trustees per year.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p01] The Board of Trustees selects the university's chancellor, who doubles as the chief academic officer and the chief executive of the university as well as serving as an ex officio voting member of the board of trustees.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p01] The chancellor is delegated with general administrative, academic, and management authority over the university.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p01] Under the chancellor are the provost and senior vice chancellor, the senior vice chancellor for health sciences, the deans of the various schools, the presidents of the regional campuses, department chairs, and the directors of university centers and institutes.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p01] The university is accredited by the Middle States Association of Colleges and Schools.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p01] Throughout its history, Pitt has been committed to a liberal arts education with a curriculum in the arts, sciences, and humanities.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p01] Pitt also has emphasized undergraduate research experience and opportunities such as co-ops and internships.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p01] Undergraduate degrees can be earned as Bachelor of Arts, Bachelor of Science, and Bachelor of Philosophy.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p01] Along with providing certificate programs, graduate level master's, professional, and doctoral degrees are also awarded.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p01] Pitt has also initiated a university-wide Outside the Classroom Curriculum (OCC) that includes a structured series of extracurricular programs and experiences designed to complement students' academic studies and help develop personal attributes and professional skills.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p01] Students who complete the OCC requirements receive an OCC "transcript" and a green cord of distinction to wear at commencement.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p01] Pitt offers free workshops and certification programs such as a pedagogy certification badge and a semester-long public education mentorship program.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p01] Distinguished undergraduate programs are offered through the David C.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p01] The freshman level entry schools include the Dietrich School of Arts and Sciences, the College of Business Administration, the Swanson School of Engineering, and the School of Nursing.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p01] News & World Report* categorizes University of Pittsburgh as "more selective".
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p01] Of those accepted, 4,399 enrolled, a yield rate (the percentage of accepted students who choose to attend the university) of 16.8%.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p01] Pitt's freshman retention rate is 93.4%, with 84.3% going on to graduate within six years.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p01] The university started test-optional admissions with the Fall 2021 incoming class in response to the COVID-19 pandemic and has extended this through Fall 2025.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p01] Of the 49% of enrolled freshmen in 2021 who submitted SAT scores; the middle 50 percent Composite scores were 1250–1470.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p01] Of the 16% of the incoming freshman class who submitted ACT scores; the middle 50 percent Composite score was between 28 and 33.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p01] Pitt is a college-sponsor of the National Merit Scholarship Program and sponsored 3 Merit Scholarship awards in 2020.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p01] In the 2020–2021 academic year, 10 freshman students were National Merit Scholars.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p01] The university's historic emphasis on international studies is physically present in its collection of 31 Nationality Rooms on the first and third floors of the Cathedral of Learning.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p01] Pitt is also one of the country's leading producers of both Fulbright scholars and Peace Corps volunteers, and one of fewer than 20 American universities to claim five or more area studies programs that have been competitively designated as National Resource Centers by the U.S.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p01] Pitt's National Resource Centers include Asian, European, Latin American, Russian and East European, and Global studies, as well as Pitt's International Business Center.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p01] In addition, Pitt's Asian Studies Center has been awarded status as a Confucius Institute by the Chinese Ministry of Education.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p01] Further, Pitt is home to one of just ten European Union Centers of Excellence in the U.S., funded by the European Commission.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p01] It does not confer degrees, but awards certificates of attainment to degree candidates in the university's schools and also operates certificate programs in African Studies (undergraduate) and in Global Studies (undergraduate & graduate).
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p01] UCIS also operates the Study Abroad Office, Nationality Rooms and Intercultural Exchange Programs.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p01] The university also offers several study abroad scholarships, including those through the Nationality Rooms program.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p01] Further, Pitt's Swanson School of Engineering has also established a joint engineering institute and program with Sichuan University in Chengdu, and Pitt's School of Medicine has established an exchange program for biomedical research students with Tsinghua University in Beijing, China.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p01] News & World Report* ranked Pitt tied of 69th out of 436 among national universities.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p01] The 2025 *Wall Street Journal/Times Higher Education* college rankings of World Universities ranked Pitt 141st overall.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p01] Pitt ranked 75th worldwide in the 2024 Center for World University Rankings.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p01] Pitt also ranked 90th worldwide in the 2024 *Academic Ranking of World Universities*.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p01] Pitt ranked 275th globally in the 2025 *QS World University Rankings*.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p01] Pitt ranks 25th of all universities in the world for the impact and performance of its 2016 scientific public publications according to the Performance Ranking of Scientific Papers for World Universities produced by the Higher Education Evaluation and Accreditation Council of Taiwan (HEEACT).
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p01] Pitt ranks as the 42nd best higher education research institution worldwide according to SCImago Institutions Rankings' 2016 World Report.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p01] Pitt's law school was ranked tied for 91st in the U.S. in 2025 by *U.S.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p01] The University of Pittsburgh School of Social Work's MSW program was ranked tied for 12th in the U.S. by *U.S.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p01] Pitt students and faculty have regularly won national and international scholarships and fellowship awards, including eight Rhodes Scholarships and ten Marshall Scholarships.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p01] In 2007, Pitt was one of only nine universities, and the only public university, to claim both Rhodes and Marshall Scholars.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p01] Since 1995, Pitt undergraduates have also won a total of five Truman Scholarships, seven Udall Scholarships, a Churchill Scholarship, a Gates Cambridge Scholarship, 43 Goldwater Scholarships, 23 Boren Scholarships, and three Mellon Humanities Fellowships.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p01] Pitt is also a leading producer of Fulbright scholars, placing in the top 20 among all universities for total number of student Fulbright scholars.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p01] Pitt alumni have won awards such as the Nobel Peace Prize, the Nobel Prize in medicine, the Pulitzer Prize for fiction, the Shaw Prize in medicine, the Albany Prize in medicine, the Fritz Medal in engineering, the Templeton Prize, and the Grainger Challenge Prize for sustainability.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p01] Pitt is a member of the Association of American Universities.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p01] The National Science Foundation ranked Pitt 18th among American universities for research and development expenditures in 2021 with $1.13 billion.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p01] Pitt is also ranked 29th in the world based on Essential Science Indicators according to the Research Center for Chinese Science Evaluation of Wuhan University.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p01] Pitt places much emphasis on undergraduate research and has integrated such research experience as a key component of its undergraduate experience.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p01] Pitt is a major center of biomedical research; in FY 2013, it ranked sixth in the nation in competitive peer-reviewed NIH funding allocations, and the University of Pittsburgh Medical Center ranked tenth among hospitals nationwide by *USNews* in 2013.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p01] Pitt neighbors the campus of Carnegie Mellon University (CMU), and in some cases, buildings of the two universities are intermingled.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p01] Further, the universities also offer multiple dual and joint degree programs such as the Medical Scientist Training Program, the Molecular Biophysics and Structural Biology Graduate Program, and the Law and Business Administration program.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p01] Some professors hold joint professorships between the two schools, and students at each university may take classes at the other (with appropriate approvals).
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p01] Pitt students and faculty also have access to the CMU library system, as well as the Carnegie Library of Pittsburgh, through the Oakland Library Consortium.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p01] The two universities also co-host academic conferences, such as the 2012 Second Language Research Forum.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p02] Undergraduate student housing comprises both traditional residence halls and apartment style housing.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p02] On the lower campus, the three cylindrical towers of the Litchfield Towers complex houses the most students on campus and contains the primary dining facility for the university.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p02] The Schenley Quadrangle, originally serving as one of city's most desirably luxury apartment complexes, comprises five separate residence halls: Amos, Brackenridge, Bruce, Holland, and McCormick.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p02] Bruce Hall houses many Honors College and Living and Learning Community (LLC) students, Holland Hall formerly served as an all female residence, and Amos Hall serves as the primary home of the university's sororities with each floor being occupied by a different Greek organization.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p02] Ruskin Hall is located near Clapp Hall and the biological complex.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p02] Completed in 2013, Nordenberg Hall is the newest residence hall houses freshmen.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p02] Forbes Hall, located on Forbes Avenue, houses mainly freshmen involved in LLCs (Living Learning Communities).
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p02] Lothrop Hall, originally built as a nursing student residence, houses students on the medical center complex.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p02] Bouquet Gardens offers garden style apartments mostly to upperclassmen.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p02] The Forbes Craig Apartments serve as the primary residence for Honors College students.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p02] The upper campus houses Sutherland Hall, home of several Living Learning Communities, as well as Panther Hall and Irvis Hall, which mainly house upperclassmen.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p02] Various fraternity housing is also found on the upper campus, as well as the Darragh Street Apartments which house medical students within a short walk to medical school's Scaife Hall.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p02] Many students, especially upperclassmen, also choose to live off campus in the nearby South Oakland neighborhood in both university and non-university owned apartments.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p02] Several traditions have become part of student life at Pitt over the years.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p02] One of the oldest traditions is "Lantern Night", an annual ceremony that serves as a formal induction for freshman women to university life.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p02] The tradition of sliding or stepping on the former home plate of Forbes Field embedded in the floor of Posvar Hall is performed by students in search of some good luck.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p02] Another good luck tradition involves rubbing the nose of the Millennium Panther outside the William Pitt Union prior to exams.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p02] A romantic tradition involves the legend stating that if lovers kiss on the steps of Heinz Memorial Chapel, they are then destined to be married there.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p02] Perhaps the most prestigious tradition involves the Omicron Delta Kappa Walk, a stone walkway between the Cathedral of Learning and Heinz Chapel that contains the engraved names of Pitt's Omicron Delta Kappa Senior of the Year award winners.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p02] Annual traditional events include "Fall Fest", and in the spring, "Bigelow Bash".
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p02] These festivals are held by the Pitt Program Council between the William Pitt Union and the Cathedral of Learning and involve a range of activities, novelties, and bands.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p02] Related to graduation, there is Honors Convocation, where awards and recognition are bestowed upon students, faculty, alumni, and staff throughout the schools and departments of the university.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p02] Also, the "Panther Sendoff" is a free annual reception typically held in Alumni Hall to congratulate each year's graduating class and wish them well.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p02] Traditions related to athletics include the "Victory Lights", where golden flood lights illuminate the top of the Cathedral of Learning after every football victory and select other athletic achievements.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p02] The Annual Bonfire and Pep Rally which is hosted by the Pitt Program Council and is held prior to a select football game.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p02] Held on the lawn of the Cathedral of Learning, it often involves the band, cheerleaders, football team, visiting dignitaries, and giveaways.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p02] Homecoming, which revolves around another home football game each year, includes a traditional fireworks and a laser-light display between the William Pitt Union and the Cathedral of Learning.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p02] The Varsity Walk, a walkway between the Cathedral of Learning and Heinz Memorial Chapel, is carved each year the names of former Pitt athletes (each year since 1950) who have promoted the university through their athletic (Panther Award) or academic (Blue-Gold Award) achievements.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p02] "Greek Week" is a yearlong initiative for the Greek organizations on campus to raise money for different charitable organizations through different events.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p02] The two biggest events each year are the Pitt Dance Marathon and Greek Sing.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p02] Yearlong fundraising activities are also held to support such charitable organizations such as the Ronald McDonald House, Make a Wish Foundation, University of Pittsburgh Cancer Institute, and the Pittsburgh Food Bank.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p02] "E-Week" is a spring celebration organized by the Engineer Student Council for a week-long series of activities and competitions to demonstrate engineering skills and foster a spirit of camaraderie.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p02] Activities include games such as Monopoly, Ingenuity, Jeopardy, Assassins, and include a talent show, relay race, mini-Olympics, and blood drive.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p02] The festivities reach climax with a parade on Friday, a soapbox derby on Saturday, and the "e-ball finale" on Saturday evening.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p02] Each engineering department competes against the others, while some smaller departments join forces.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p02] Pitt Arts is a program founded by the university in 1997 to encourage students to explore and connect to the art and cultural opportunities of the City of Pittsburgh via three programs.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p02] Art Encounters provides trips to arts events for undergrads that include free tickets, transportation, a catered reception, and encounters with international artists and thinkers.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p02] Free Visits grants undergrad and grad students free admission using their Pitt IDs to the Carnegie Museum of Art, Carnegie Museum of Natural History, Senator John Heinz History Center, Phipps Conservatory, Mattress Factory, and the Andy Warhol Museum.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p02] Various student theater groups convene at Pitt.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p02] University of Pittsburgh Stages is the production company of the Department of Theatre Arts which puts public student performances of classic masterpieces, contemporary productions, and student-directed labs.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p02] It also runs the Shakespeare-in-the-Schools which tours classic theater for K-12 students throughout the Pittsburgh area.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p02] *Friday Nite Improvs*, Pittsburgh's longest-running theatre show, was started in 1989 by graduate theatre students.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p02] It takes place weekly inside the Cathedral of Learning's studio theatre.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p02] The Redeye Theatre Project is a festival of one-act plays cast, written, and rehearsed in 24 hours.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p02] Pitt Musical Theater Club provides undergraduates the opportunity to perform in student-directed variety shows and musicals.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p02] The Pitt Men's Glee Club, founded in 1890, is the oldest extracurricular club on campus.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p02] The University of Pittsburgh Women's Choral Ensemble, founded in 1927, is open to all women of the university including undergraduates, graduate students, and staff.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p02] The ensemble leads the traditional lamplighter processional each fall and performs repertory ranging from traditional sacred and secular classics to international folk songs, popular music, and show tunes.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p02] Heinz Chapel Choir is an accomplished and internationally known *a cappella* choir consisting entirely of Pitt students that has been performing for over 70 years.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p02] Pitt Pendulums, founded in 1996, is a co-ed a cappella group, the oldest a cappella group on campus.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p02] Other a cappella groups on campus include C Flat Run, a co-ed group; Pittch Please, an all-male group; Pitches and Tones, a co-ed group; The Songburghs, a co-ed group; and Sounds Like Treble, an all-female group.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p02] All groups on campus regularly perform in various on and off-campus functions and are regular competitors in the ICCA's, the International Championship of Collegiate A Cappella.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p02] Most recently, The Songburghs won first place at the ICCA Central Quarterfinal on February 2, 2019.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p02] They also went on to place third at the next round, the ICCA Central Semifinal at the University at Buffalo on March 30, 2019.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p02] Carpathian Ensemble, founded within the Department of Music in 1786, performs Gypsy, Klezmer, Armenian, Moldavian, Ukrainian, and Macedonian music.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p02] The University Gamelan, established in 1995, is the largest Sundanese gamelan program in the U.S. and has sponsored an artist-in-residency program each year since 1998.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p02] The University of Pittsburgh Orchestra performs several concerts and consists of music students, students from the university at large, faculty, staff, and members of the metropolitan community.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p02] The orchestra performs not only works of the standard art music literature, but also new works of student composers.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p02] Pitt Jazz Ensemble, founded in 1969 by saxophonist Dr.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p02] Pitt African Music and Dance Ensemble, founded in 1983 by a Ghanaian ethnomusicologist Willie O.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p02] Anku, specializes in music and dances from Africa.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p02] Pitt Band, founded in 1911, is the varsity marching band of the University of Pittsburgh.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p02] There are over 350 student clubs and organizations at the University of Pittsburgh.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p02] In April 2024, Pittsburgh University students joined other campuses in encampments and protests against the Israel–Hamas war.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p02] The protestors called for an end to the genocide in Gaza, for the university to divest financially from the "Israeli apartheid regime" and cut ties with all Israeli universities.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p02] CAIR-Pittsburgh called on the University of Pittsburgh to drop charges against students who protested against Israel's genocide in Gaza.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p02] The protests continued into the next academic year, with faculty accusing the administration of racism because of the difference in response to the wars in Ukraine and Gaza.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p02] There are presently over 40 general, or social, fraternities and sororities on campus.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p02] The oldest men's fraternity, Phi Gamma Delta first held events in 1863, while the oldest women's group, Kappa Alpha Theta, was established in 1915.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p02] Additionally, a similar number of professional, service, and honor societies are present on campus.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p02] The oldest are the medical fraternity Phi Beta Pi, entering in 1891, and the dental fraternity Psi Omega, entering in 1897.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p02] The historically black fraternities Alpha Phi Alpha (1913) and Alpha Kappa Alpha (1918) came later.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p02] All varsity sports teams compete as members of the Atlantic Coast Conference (ACC) since the 2013–14 season, with the exception of the gymnastics team which moved to the ACC when the conference began sponsoring the sport in 2023.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p02] The university also maintains membership in the Eastern College Athletic Conference (ECAC).
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p02] Pitt athletes have received a total of five Olympic medals.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p02] There are approximately 28 additional athletic teams that compete at the non-varsity club sports level.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p02] Pitt's highest-profile athletic programs, football and men's basketball, are consistently competitive.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p02] Pitt has been regularly ranked as having one of the best combinations of football and basketball programs by multiple sports media outlets, including CBS Sports, ESPN, and *Sports Illustrated*.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p02] In the fall of 1909, the University of Pittsburgh was the first college or university to adopt the panther (*Puma concolor*) as its mascot.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p02] Popular as photo sites, there are ten representations of Panthers in and about Pitt's campus, and ten more painted fiberglass panthers placed around the campus by the Pitt Student Government.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p02] These fiberglass panther structures are given to a campus group for a year and painted by the group to reflect their interests.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p02] The oldest representations are four panthers that guard each corner of the Panther Hollow bridge.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p02] Traditionally the most popular sport at the University of Pittsburgh, football has been played at the highest levels at the university since 1890.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p02] During the more than 100 years of competitive football at Pitt, the university has helped pioneer the sport by, among other things, instituting the use of numbers on jerseys and desegregating the Sugar Bowl with Bobby Grier.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p02] Among the top schools in terms of all-time wins, Pitt teams have claimed nine National Championships and boast 88 players that have been chosen as first-team All-Americans.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p02] Since 2015, the head coach of the football team has been Pat Narduzzi.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p02] Pitt first sponsored varsity men's basketball in 1905 and became an early national power after winning two Helms Foundation National Championships in 1927–28 and 1929–30.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p02] Those teams, coached by the innovative and legendary Naismith Hall of Fame inductee "Doc" Carlson, were led by National Player of the Year and Hall of Famer Charlie Hyatt.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p02] Following a Final Four appearance in 1941, Pitt appeared in a handful of NCAA tournaments throughout the 1950s, 1960s, and 1970s, including an Elite Eight appearance in 1974 led by All-American Billy Knight.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p02] Pitt joined the Big East Conference in 1982, and by the end of the decade had secured a pair of Big East regular season championships led by All-Americans Charles Smith and Jerome Lane.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p02] In the 2000s (decade), led by coach Jamie Dixon, an era of consistent national and conference competitiveness has been achieved, including reaching the number one ranking in various national polls.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p02] Since 2002, Pitt has appeared in eleven NCAA tournaments advancing to five Sweet Sixteens and an Elite Eight.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p02] During this time, prior to joining the Atlantic Coast Conference in 2013, Pitt and has won three Big East regular season championships, two Big East Tournament Championships, and has advanced to six Big East Tournament Championship games.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p02] The Pittsburgh Panthers women's varsity basketball program started during the 1914–1915 school year and lasted until 1927 before going on hiatus until 1970.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p02] Pitt's women's team has posted several NCAA, NWIT, and EAIAW tournament appearances.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p02] Led head coach Agnus Berenato, Pitt has played in post-season tournaments each of the last five seasons, including three NCAA Tournaments appearances where it advanced to the Sweet Sixteen in 2008 and 2009.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p02] The head coach of the men's basketball team is Jeff Capel.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p02] Pitt has a long history of success in other intercollegiate athletic events.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p02] In Track and Field, Pitt has produced several Olympic and NCAA champions such as 800 m Olympic gold medalist John Woodruff, two-time 110 m hurdle Olympic gold medalist Roger Kingdom, and seven-time NCAA champion and 2005 World Champion triple jumper Trecia-Kaye Smith.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p02] The wrestling program has a rich history and is among the leaders in producing individual national champions with 16.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p02] Pitt's women's volleyball team, one of the winningest program in the nation, won 11 conference championships while a member of the Big East, and 6 ACC championships and appeared in 20 NCAA tournaments and four final fours since the program began in 1974.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p02] Pitt's swimming and diving teams have produced several Olympians and won 19 men's and nine women's Big East Championships while a member of that conference.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p02] Pitt women's gymnastics is a regular qualifier for the NCAA Northeast Regional Championship.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p02] Baseball, Pitt's oldest varsity sport, has produced several major league players and has reached the national 25 repeatedly, including in 2013.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p02] Other varsity sports have also competed at national and conference championships and include cross country, soccer, softball, and tennis.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p02] The University of Pittsburgh Varsity Marching Band was founded in 1911 and performs at athletic and other events.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p02] The Pitt Cheerleading squad has won multiple cheerleading national championships, including three straight from 1992 to 1994.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p02] The Pitt dance team also has been competitive in national competitions.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p02] University faculty have been pioneers in such fields as virology (Jonas Salk), astronomy (John Brashear), aviation (Samuel Pierpont Langley), and psychology (Benjamin Spock).
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p02] The university has been home to faculty members deemed the "fathers" of various fields, such as the "father of radio broadcasting" (Reginald Fessenden), the "father of project management" (David I.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p02] Cleland), the "father of CPR" (Peter Safar), and the "father of organ transplantation" (Thomas Starzl).
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p02] The university is also notable for its faculty in philosophy.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p02] The university is the namesake of the Pittsburgh School, which was founded by Wilfrid Sellars, a significant figure in analytic philosophy.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p02] Current notable faculty in the philosophy department include John McDowell, Robert Brandom, and Nicholas Rescher.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p02] There have been 31 university heads for the University of Pittsburgh.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p02] Beginning in the institution's academy days, the head of the school was referred to as Principal, a title that was retained until 1872 when it was changed to Chancellor by an alteration to the university's charter.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p02] This title of Chancellor has lasted except for a brief change during Wesley Posvar's administration when it was switched to president.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p02] As of 2019, the University of Pittsburgh has over 330,000 living alumni who are supported by the Pitt Alumni Association, founded in 1866, and over 50 regionally-based Pitt Clubs located throughout the world.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p02] Three Pitt alumni have been awarded the Nobel Prize: Paul Lauterbur '62 for his work in magnetic resonance imaging, Philip Hench '20 for discovery of the hormone cortisone, and Wangari Maathai '66 for founding the Green Belt Movement.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p02] Other alumni have also been pioneers in their respective fields, including John Wistar Simpson '41, a pioneer in nuclear energy, and Vladimir Zworykin '26, who has been regarded as the "father of television".
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p02] National Medal of Science winners include Bert W.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p02] O'Malley '59 & '63, a pioneer in steroid hormones, and Herbert Boyer '63, Genentech founder and biotech pioneer; while Leonard Baker '52, Michael Chabon '84, and Brandon Som '02 have won the Pulitzer Prize.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p02] Pitt alumni who have excelled in professional sports include Pro Football Hall of Fame inductees Dan Marino '83, Mike Ditka '61, and Tony Dorsett '77.
[src:university-of-pittsburgh/university-of-pittsburgh-p02] Basketball Hall of Fame inductees include pioneering coach Clifford Carlson '18 & '20 while others, such as John Woodruff '39 and Roger Kingdom '02, have won Olympic gold.
